Twitter Authorization Step

# set the authorisation token you previously saved with rtweet_app()
# (see Twitter Scraper.Rmd file) for the rest of the session:
my_oauth <- auth_as("my_oauth")

Collecting tweets by hashtag

the search_tweets function from rtweets allows to perform this task from the rest API. The rate limit should be 18,000 per minute. it samples from recent days (up to past 6/9 days).

rishi_tweets <- search_tweets("sunak", 
                                n = 10000,
                                include_rts = FALSE,
                                geocode=NULL,
                                retryonratelimit = TRUE,
                                token = my_oauth)

# search for 1000 tweets (no retweets) with brexit hashtag from London
brexit_tweets <- search_tweets("#brexit", 
                               n = 1000, 
                               include_rts = FALSE,
                               geocode = '51.51413,-0.11534,10km', #London latitude, longitude & radius we want around it (in km)
                               retryonratelimit = TRUE,
                               token = my_oauth)

To visualise frequency over-time

ts_plot(rishi_tweets, "0.5 hours") + ggplot2::theme_minimal() + ggplot2::theme(plot.title = ggplot2::element_text(face = "bold")) +
    ggplot2::labs(x = NULL, y = NULL, title = "Half-hourly frequency of recent Twitter statuses about Rishi Sunak",
        subtitle = "Twitter status (tweet) counts aggregated using half-hour intervals",
        caption = "\nSource: Data collected from Twitter's REST API via rtweet")

Introducing: Wordclouds!

The code below installs the required text analysis package (quanteda.textplots) and then transforms the Brexit tweet object into a corpus object and then into a dfm object - where going to learn all about corpus/dfm objects when well introduce text mining in the coming weeks! In the dfm object step, we can remove words that are not particularly meaningful for our aims (e.g.stopwords etc.). With the function textplot_wordcloud we can then generate a wordcloud. The function also allows to specify formatting options, sich as size, total number of words to be included, color 

if (!("quanteda.textplots" %in% installed.packages())) {
    install.packages("quanteda.textplots")
}
library("quanteda.textplots")

if (!("quanteda" %in% installed.packages())) {
    install.packages("quanteda")
}
library("quanteda")


# step 1: remove emoticons (using regular expression for
# emojis/non-ASCII characters)
rishi_tweets$text <- gsub("[^\001-\177]", "", rishi_tweets$text)

# step 2: further text data cleaning + dfm transformation

rishi_corpus <- corpus(rishi_tweets$text)

tweet_dfm <- tokens(rishi_corpus, remove_punct = TRUE, remove_symbols = T,
    remove_numbers = T, remove_url = T, remove_twitter = T) %>%
    dfm()
